Here's a Java subroutine that computes the standard deviation of an array of floating-point numbers. The method follows the established naming conventions, structure, and formatting standards as outlined.

```java
public class StatisticsCalculator {

    /**
     * Computes the standard deviation of an array of floating-point numbers.
     *
     * @param data an array of float values
     * @return the standard deviation of the provided values
     * @throws IllegalArgumentException if the input array is null or empty
     */
    public static double computeStandardDeviation(float[] data) {
        if (data == null || data.length == 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input array must not be null or empty.");
        }

        double sum = 0.0;
        double mean;
        double varianceSum = 0.0;

        // Calculate the sum of the data points
        for (float value : data) {
            sum += value;
        }

        // Calculate the mean
        mean = sum / data.length;

        // Calculate the sum of squared differences from the mean
        for (float value : data) {
            varianceSum += Math.pow(value - mean, 2);
        }

        // Calculate variance and then standard deviation
        double variance = varianceSum / data.length;
        return Math.sqrt(variance);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
