Here's a Java subroutine that calculates the standard deviation of a set of floating-point values, adhering to the specified coding standards:

```java
/**
 * Calculates the standard deviation of a given array of floating-point numbers.
 * 
 * @param data Array of floating-point values to calculate standard deviation
 * @return Standard deviation of the input array, or Double.NaN if array is empty
 * @throws IllegalArgumentException if input array is null
 */
public static double calculateStandardDeviation(float[] data) {
    // Validate input array
    if (data == null) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input array cannot be null");
    }

    // Handle empty array case
    if (data.length == 0) {
        return Double.NaN;
    }

    // Calculate mean
    double sum = 0.0;
    for (float value : data) {
        sum += value;
    }
    double mean = sum / data.length;

    // Calculate variance
    double sumSquaredDifferences = 0.0;
    for (float value : data) {
        double difference = value - mean;
        sumSquaredDifferences += difference * difference;
    }

    // Calculate standard deviation
    double variance = sumSquaredDifferences / data.length;
    return Math.sqrt(variance);
}

// Example usage
public static void main(String[] args) {
    float[] data = {3.3f, 5.6f, 7.8f, 5.4f, 9.9f};
    double standardDeviation = calculateStandardDeviation(data);
    System.out.printf("Standard Deviation: %.4f%n", standardDeviation);
}
```

