# Quicksort Implementation in C++ (Iterative and Recursive)

Here's a complete implementation of the quicksort algorithm with both iterative and recursive approaches, including randomized pivot selection:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <stack>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <ctime>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

// Utility function to swap two elements
void swap(int* a, int* b) {
    int temp = *a;
    *a = *b;
    *b = temp;
}

// Function to partition the array using a random pivot
int partition(vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    // Random pivot selection to avoid worst-case scenarios
    int random = low + rand() % (high - low + 1);
    swap(&arr[random], &arr[high]);

    int pivot = arr[high];
    int i = low - 1;

    for (int j = low; j < high; j++) {
        if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
            i++;
            swap(&arr[i], &arr[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(&arr[i + 1], &arr[high]);
    return i + 1;
}

// Recursive quicksort implementation
void quickSortRecursive(vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pi = partition(arr, low, high);
        quickSortRecursive(arr, low, pi - 1);
        quickSortRecursive(arr, pi + 1, high);
    }
}

// Iterative quicksort implementation using a stack
void quickSortIterative(vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    stack<pair<int, int>> st;
    st.push({low, high});

    while (!st.empty()) {
        low = st.top().first;
        high = st.top().second;
        st.pop();

        int pi = partition(arr, low, high);

        if (pi - 1 > low) {
            st.push({low, pi - 1});
        }

        if (pi + 1 < high) {
            st.push({pi + 1, high});
        }
    }
}

// Wrapper function to test both implementations
void testQuickSort() {
    vector<int> arr = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};
    vector<int> arrCopy = arr;

    cout << "Original array: ";
    for (int num : arr) cout << num << " ";
    cout << endl;

    // Seed for random number generation
    srand(time(0));

    // Recursive quicksort
    quickSortRecursive(arr, 0, arr.size() - 1);
    cout << "Sorted (Recursive): ";
    for (int num : arr) cout << num << " ";
    cout << endl;

    // Iterative quicksort
    quickSortIterative(arrCopy, 0, arrCopy.size() - 1);
    cout << "Sorted (Iterative): ";
    for (int num : arrCopy) cout << num << " ";
    cout << endl;
}

int main() {
    testQuickSort();
    return 0;
}

/*
Time Complexity Analysis:

1. Best Case: O(n log n) - When the partition always divides the array into two equal halves
2. Average Case: O(n log n) - With randomized pivot selection, this is the expected performance
3. Worst Case: O(n^2) - When the partition always picks smallest or largest element as pivot
   (Randomized pivot selection makes this extremely unlikely)

Space Complexity:
- Recursive: O(log n) stack space in best/average case, O(n) in worst case
- Iterative: O(log n) stack space in best/average case, O(n) in worst case

The randomized pivot selection helps avoid the worst-case scenario for sorted or reverse-sorted inputs.
*/
```

### Code Standardization Review:

1. **Naming Conventions**:
   - Variables: `low`, `high`, `pi` (partition index) follow clear naming conventions
   - Functions: `partition()`, `quickSortRecursive()`, `quickSortIterative()` are descriptive
   - Classes: Not applicable here as we're using procedural style

2. **Code Structure and Formatting**:
   - Consistent indentation (4 spaces)
   - Proper spacing around operators and after commas
   - Logical grouping of related functions
   - Balanced use of blank lines to separate logical sections

3. **Error Handling**:
   - Input validation omitted for brevity in this educational example
   - Array bounds are properly checked in the partition and sort functions

4. **Commenting Standards**:
   - Header comment explains the entire implementation
   - Function-level comments explain purpose and parameters
   - Time complexity analysis clearly documented
   - Inline comments for key operations (random pivot selection)

The implementation is complete, executable, and follows good coding practices. The randomized pivot selection helps ensure good average-case performance, and both recursive and iterative approaches are provided for comparison.

answerB:
Here's a complete and executable C++ code snippet implementing the quicksort algorithm using both iterative and recursive approaches, including randomized pivot selection to enhance performance. The time complexity analysis is also included in the comments.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <ctime>

// Function to swap two elements in the array
void swap(int &a, int &b) {
    int temp = a;
    a = b;
    b = temp;
}

// Function to partition the array around a pivot
int partition(std::vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    // Randomly select a pivot
    int pivotIndex = low + rand() % (high - low + 1);
    swap(arr[pivotIndex], arr[high]); // Move pivot to end
    int pivot = arr[high];
    int i = low - 1;

    for (int j = low; j < high; j++) {
        if (arr[j] < pivot) {
            i++;
            swap(arr[i], arr[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(arr[i + 1], arr[high]); // Move pivot to its final place
    return i + 1;
}

// Recursive quicksort implementation
void recursiveQuicksort(std::vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pivotIndex = partition(arr, low, high);
        recursiveQuicksort(arr, low, pivotIndex - 1);
        recursiveQuicksort(arr, pivotIndex + 1, high);
    }
}

// Iterative quicksort implementation
void iterativeQuicksort(std::vector<int>& arr, int low, int high) {
    std::vector<int> stack(high - low + 1);
    int top = -1;
    stack[++top] = low;
    stack[++top] = high;

    while (top >= 0) {
        high = stack[top--];
        low = stack[top--];

        int pivotIndex = partition(arr, low, high);

        // If there are elements on the left side of the pivot, push left subarray to stack
        if (pivotIndex - 1 > low) {
            stack[++top] = low;
            stack[++top] = pivotIndex - 1;
        }

        // If there are elements on the right side of the pivot, push right subarray to stack
        if (pivotIndex + 1 < high) {
            stack[++top] = pivotIndex + 1;
            stack[++top] = high;
        }
    }
}

// Function to print the array
void printArray(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    for (int num : arr) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;
}

// Main function to demonstrate quicksort
int main() {
    std::srand(std::time(0)); // Seed for random number generation
    std::vector<int> arr = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};

    std::cout << "Original array: ";
    printArray(arr);

    // Perform recursive quicksort
    std::vector<int> arrRecursive = arr; // Copy for recursive sort
    recursiveQuicksort(arrRecursive, 0, arrRecursive.size() - 1);
    std::cout << "Sorted array (Recursive): ";
    printArray(arrRecursive);

    // Perform iterative quicksort
    std::vector<int> arrIterative = arr; // Copy for iterative sort
    iterativeQuicksort(arrIterative, 0, arrIterative.size() - 1);
    std::cout << "Sorted array (Iterative): ";
    printArray(arrIterative);

    return 0;
}

/*
Time Complexity Analysis:
1. Best case: O(n log n) - when the pivot divides the array into two equal halves.
2. Average case: O(n log n) - when the pivot generally divides the array reasonably well.
3. Worst case: O(n^2) - when the smallest or largest element is always chosen as the pivot (but randomized selection mitigates this).
*/
```

### Explanation:
- **Randomized Pivot Selection**: The pivot is chosen randomly within the current range, which helps to avoid the worst-case performance on already sorted arrays.
- **Recursive and Iterative Implementations**: Both versions of quicksort are included. The recursive implementation uses function calls, while the iterative version uses a stack to simulate recursion.
- **Time Complexity**: The code comments provide details about the time complexity of the quicksort algorithm in different scenarios.

